Package org.microbean.type

Class TypeSet

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractSet<Type>
        • org.microbean.type.TypeSet
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<Type>, Collection<Type>, Set<Type>
    public class TypeSet
extends AbstractSet<Type>
    An unmodifiable AbstractSet of Types with additional convenient functionality.

    Iteration over any TypeSet instance is guaranteed to be in some deterministic but otherwise unspecified order. The order is subject to change between versions of this class.

    Author:
    Laird Nelson

      • getRawTypes

        public final SortedSet<Class<?>> getRawTypes()
        Returns a non-null, unmodifiable SortedSet of all raw types contained directly or indirectly by this TypeSet.

        This method calls the getClasses() and getInterfaces() methods as part of its operation.

        Returns:
        a non-null, unmodifiable SortedSet of all raw types contained directly or indirectly by this TypeSet
        See Also:
        getClasses(), getInterfaces()
        Idempotency:
        This method is idempotent and deterministic. The Set that is returned consists of elements in a particular, but deliberately unspecified, order that is not dependent upon the ordering of the Set of Types initially supplied to this TypeSet.
        Nullability:
        This method never returns null.
        Thread Safety:
        This method is safe for concurrent use by multiple threads.

      • getMostSpecializedInterface

        public final Class<?> getMostSpecializedInterface()
        Returns an arbitrarily selected Class that is guaranteed to be the most specialized interface in its type hierarchy drawn from the interfaces in this TypeSet, or null if this TypeSet contains no interfaces.

        The Class that is returned is guaranteed to return true from its Class.isInterface() method.

        For example, if a TypeSet contains Closeable.class and AutoCloseable.class, then this method will return Closeable.class. If a TypeSet contains AutoCloseable.class and Serializable.class, then either AutoCloseable.class or Serializable.class will be returned.

        Returns:
        an arbitrarily selected Class that is guaranteed to be the most specialized interface in its type hierarchy drawn from the interfaces in this TypeSet, or null
        See Also:
        getMostSpecializedClass()
        Idempotency:
        This method is idempotent and deterministic.
        Nullability:
        This method may return null.
        Thread Safety:
        This method is safe for concurrent use by multiple threads.

      • getMostSpecializedGenericInterface

        public final Type getMostSpecializedGenericInterface()
        Returns an arbitrarily selected Type that is guaranteed to be a Type representing the most specialized interface in its type hierarchy drawn from the interfaces in this TypeSet, or null if this TypeSet contains no interfaces.

        The Class that is represented indirectly by the return value is guaranteed to return true from its Class.isInterface() method.

        For example, if a TypeSet contains Closeable.class and AutoCloseable.class, then this method will return Closeable.class. If a TypeSet contains AutoCloseable.class and Serializable.class, then either AutoCloseable.class or Serializable.class will be returned.

        Returns:
        an arbitrarily selected Type that is guaranteed to be a Type representing the most specialized interface in its type hierarchy drawn from the interfaces in this TypeSet, or null; the Type returned is guaranteed to be either a Class or a ParameterizedType
        See Also:
        getMostSpecializedClass()
        Idempotency:
        This method is idempotent and deterministic.
        Nullability:
        This method may return null.
        Thread Safety:
        This method is safe for concurrent use by multiple threads.

      • getMostSpecializedClass

        public final Class<?> getMostSpecializedClass()
        Returns an arbitrarily selected Class that is guaranteed to be the most specialized subclass in its type hierarchy drawn from the classes in this TypeSet.

        For example, if a TypeSet contains Integer.class, Number.class and Object.class, then this method will return Integer.class. If a TypeSet contains Integer.class and String.class, then either Integer.class or String.class will be returned.

        In practice, most TypeSets in normal use contain classes from a single inheritance hierarchy.

        Returns:
        an arbitrarily selected Class that is guaranteed to be the most specialized subclass in its type hierarchy drawn from the classes in this TypeSet; never null
        See Also:
        getMostSpecializedInterface()
        Idempotency:
        This method is idempotent and deterministic.
        Nullability:
        This method never returns null.
        Thread Safety:
        This method is safe for concurrent use by multiple threads.

      • getMostSpecializedGenericClass

        public final Type getMostSpecializedGenericClass()
        Returns an arbitrarily selected Type that is guaranteed to represent the most specialized subclass in its type hierarchy drawn from the classes in this TypeSet.

        For example, if a TypeSet contains Integer.class, Number.class and Object.class, then this method will return Integer.class. If a TypeSet contains Integer.class and String.class, then either Integer.class or String.class will be returned.

        In practice, most TypeSets in normal use contain classes from a single inheritance hierarchy.

        Returns:
        an arbitrarily selected Type that is guaranteed to represent the most specialized subclass in its type hierarchy drawn from the classes in this TypeSet; never null; the Type returned is guaranteed to be either a Class or a ParameterizedType
